    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper proposes that the 2025 LIGO-Virgo-KAGRA detection of a black-hole merger (GW250114) \u2014 which confirmed that total black-hole horizon area grows during mergers \u2014 can be used to sharply restrict the design of quantum gravity theories if that growth law is treated as exact. The review board found the core idea timely and non-trivial, as constraining quantum-scale theories using macroscopic gravitational-wave data is a genuinely novel diagnostic. However, several technical steps are omitted or incomplete in the four-page format, and the most fundamental concern is that the observational input itself relies on assuming Einstein gravity to infer horizon areas, creating a circularity when those areas are used to constrain non-Einstein theories. The paper is best read as a provocative no-go argument that requires further expert verification before its conclusions can be treated as established.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper argues that postulating exact Hawking area monotonicity in Stelle gravity and nonlocal/fractional quantum gravity (NLQG/FQG) forces: (i) vanishing action coefficients \u03b2\u2081 and \u03b2\u2082 for R\u00b2 and (Riemann)\u00b2 terms when non-Ricci-flat black hole solutions exist; (ii) absence of extra real poles in the FQG graviton propagator; and (iii) positivity of the inverse nonlocal operator's spectral representation. The Ricci-flat compatibility result is the cleanest claim, following directly from the fact that Schwarzschild/Kerr are exact solutions when \u03b2\u2082=0. The non-Ricci-flat constraint is derived from a low-curvature focusing condition (Eq. 10) in which curvature-squared terms are dropped \u2014 a sufficient but not necessary condition. The covariant Wald entropy extension to fractional form factors uses horizon geometric identities (e.g., f(\u25a1)R|_bifurcation = f(0)R|_bifurcation) that are asserted without proof for infinite-derivative operators. The FQG positivity condition is explicitly deferred to future work. The conclusion that Wald entropy monotonically tracks dynamical event-horizon area is stated without establishing the equivalence between stationary Noether-charge entropy and dynamical second-law entropy in this modified-gravity context."
    }
